Reason: Target compound: 2-phenyl-1-propene. Basic unit, propene has a melting point of -185.2°C. Addition of a phenyl group increases intermolecular forces due to the added pi-stacking potential and larger molecular size, which we can estimate to raise the melting point by approximately +150°C. However, the presence of a double bond in the propene part of the molecule can slightly lower the melting point due to less effective packing, which we can estimate as -5°C. Overall, the molecule is nonpolar; hence, van der Waals interactions are the main intermolecular forces. The alkene and aromatic ring contribute to the melting point positively, but the effect of the double bond is relatively minor compared to the phenyl group.
